Why the Error Happens

Example in your Blade view:

<h2>{{ $post->title }}</h2>
<p>{{ $post->content }}</p>

But in your controller you returned:

return view('post');

Since $post was not passed, Laravel shows:

Undefined variable $post



2.Correct Controller Code

Open your controller (example: PostController.php)

use App\Models\Post;

public function show($id)
{
    $post = Post::find($id);

    return view('post', compact('post'));
}

Now $post is passed to the view.



3.Route Example

Check your route in routes/web.php

Route::get('/post/{id}', [PostController::class, 'show']);



4. Blade View Example

Your view file:

resources/views/post.blade.php
<h2>{{ $post->title }}</h2>

<p>{{ $post->content }}</p>

Now Laravel knows what $post is.

5. If Error Happens Inside Loop

Sometimes the error happens because of a wrong variable name.

Wrong:

@foreach($posts as $p)

<h2>{{ $post->title }}</h2>

@endforeach

Correct:

@foreach($posts as $post)

<h2>{{ $post->title }}</h2>

@endforeach



6. Safe Method (Avoid Error)

You can also check if $post exists.

@if(isset($post))

<h2>{{ $post->title }}</h2>

@endif



7. Example Working Flow


Controller:

public function show($id)
{
    $post = Post::with('comments')->findOrFail($id);

    return view('posts.show', compact('post'));
}

Blade:

<h1>{{ $post->title }}</h1>

<p>{{ $post->content }}</p>

<h3>Comments</h3>

@foreach($post->comments as $comment)

<p>{{ $comment->comment }}</p>

@endforeach
